Phase 2: Enable I2S Audio on the Pi

SSH into your Pi:
ssh pi@your-pi-ip

Edit the Boot Config:

sudo nano /boot/config.txt
# Note: On Raspberry Pi OS Bookworm, use: sudo nano /boot/firmware/config.txt

Uncomment (or add) this line at the bottom:

dtparam=i2s=on

Save & Exit: Press Ctrl+X, then Y, then Enter.
Compile the I2S Module (This enables the "Dummy" driver so the Pi sees the mic):
# Run this single long command to create the module loader
sudo curl -L https://raw.githubusercontent.com/shreyasssrai/ArrayButton/main/i2s_mic_module.sh | bash

Note: If the link above doesn't work, typically you just need to load snd-i2s-rpi-simple. For now, let's assume standard I2S activation. If you are on a fresh OS, just enabling dtparam=i2s=on is often enough for raw access, but installing the rpi-i2s-audio loader is better).
Alternative (Easier): Edit /etc/modules:
sudo nano /etc/modules
Add:
snd-bcm2835

Reboot the Pi:
sudo reboot

Verify Microphone: After rebooting, run:
arecord -l
You should see a card listed (often Card 0 or Card 1 named snd_rpi_i2s_card or similar).

Phase 3: Install Software & Dependencies
Update System:  sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y 
Install System Audio Libraries:  sudo apt install python3-pip python3-venv libatlas-base-dev portaudio19-dev -y 
Create a Virtual Environment (Recommended for Pi OS Bookworm):  python3 -m venv venv
     source venv/bin/activate
 
Install Python Libraries:  pip install sounddevice vosk requests rapidfuzz word2number 
